==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cereus
<hw>Ce"re*us</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., a wax
candle, fr. <ets>cera</ets> wax. So named from the resemblance of one
species to the columnar shape of a wax candle.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<def>A genus of plants of the Cactus family. They are natives of
America, from California to Chili.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Although several species flower in the night, the name
<stype>Night-blooming cereus</stype> is specially applied to the
<spn>Cereus grandiflorus</spn>, which is cultivated for its beautiful,
shortlived flowers. The <spn>Cereus giganteus</spn>, whose columnar
trunk is sometimes sixty feet in height, is a striking feature of the
scenery of New Mexico, Texas, etc.<-- saguaro?= Carnegiea gigantea
--></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cerevis</ent>⟦br⟧
